<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  What story does a landscape tell — and how do you read it like a geologist?
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Unit 2 launches <strong>Thread 4 — Science-Policy-Public</strong>. For the first time, students write for a non-student audience: a hypothetical Greater Chennai Corporation planning meeting. The format choice (≤1500-word written, ≤6-min annotated Google Earth video, or large infographic) is deliberate UDL design — the rubric is identical across all three, so the deliverable assesses landscape-reading thinking, not writing stamina.</p>
  <p>It also continues <strong>Thread 1 — OPVL</strong> with new source types: USGS, Geological Survey of India, ISRO Bhuvan satellite data, historical Google Earth imagery, and Chennai-local news. The geological-time perspective added in Block 3 lets students compare evidence across timescales their U0 + U1 sources never spanned.</p>
  <p>Nine blocks, nine locations, one new AI partner (the <a href="/ai-partners/field-geologist/">Field Geologist</a>). The summative — the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a> — is the structured biography. The planning-audience share-out in Block 9 is the second defense in the year-long defense arc and the first one with a non-academic audience role.</p>
</div>

